	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Good prospects for cocoa prices</h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 July 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At the end of May, the International Cocoa Organization (ICCO) raised its estimates of world production to 3.99 million tonnes as grindings stayed stable, reducing the projected supply deficit by 28,000 tonnes to 43,000 tonnes. While cocoa prices fell by 1.8% and 2.3% on London and New York markets respectively in the midst of a global economic crisis exacerbated by the EU financial turmoil, Commerzbank warned of possible El Niño effects on production which may see the production deficit rise in 2012/13. This led Rabobank to project an increase in cocoa prices.</p><p>According to Rabobank, the deficit will arise as a result in part of expanding demand in Asia and in part of policy changes in Côte d’Ivoire, ‘despite bumper stocks still left over from the 2010/11 season’. Rabobank forecasts global cocoa production for the 2012/13 season at approximately 4.1 million tonnes, in the face of ‘a 3.1% increase in global consumption to 4.2 million tonnes resulting in a forecast deficit of 89,000 tonnes’.&nbsp;</p><p>Growth in confectionery consumption in Asia, and more generally in Brazil, Russia, India and China (BRIC countries), is outpacing growth in developed markets. According to the director of cocoa and sustainability of the Blommer Chocolate Company, the company expects global cocoa demand to grow by 2.5% in the 2011/12 crop year, largely due to demand from the BRIC countries. However this is only half the 4.8% rise in 2010/11 and well below the 34-year average of 3.1%, as appetites in the mature European and North American markets remain constrained. This accounts for ICCO’s cautious forecast of world grindings.&nbsp;</p><p>On the production side, efforts are continuing to expand sustainable cocoa production in West Africa. In May 2012, the World Cocoa Foundation announced the launch of a US$4 million initiative to provide funds for an expansion of smallholder cocoa production in three West and Central African producers, Côte d’Ivoire, Nigeria and Cameroon. The initiative is being co-financed with member companies, the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation and the Sustainable Trade Initiative. It includes text-message-based advisory services on fertiliser application, plant husbandry and harvesting techniques, as well as credit for inputs.&nbsp;</p><p>In Ghana, the African Export-Import bank is providing US$54 million in loans to expand cocoa bean processing capacity. This follows similar support to two processing facilities in Côte d’Ivoire to the value of US$40 million. In the case of Ghana, the Cocoa Board is seeking to double cocoa production in the coming years. This needs to be seen against the background of Africa emerging for the first time in 2011/12 ahead of Europe as the major processor of cocoa beans. According to ICCO, African grindings are set to reach 1.68 million tonnes, some 15,000 tonnes greater than European grindings. This is seen as ‘ending decades of dominance by processing industries centred largely in Germany and around Amsterdam’. According to Agrimoney.com, this ‘reflects in part the “uncertainty of the global economic situation, combined with sluggish growth predictions and deteriorating processing margins” which are depressing output in Europe’, and in part moves supported by the World Bank to expand grinding capacity in producing countries, to enable them to reap the benefits of ‘processing margins’. It also reflects greater use of locally processed cocoa beans in value-added processing industries in West Africa. ICCO is now urging Nigerian manufacturers to expand local processing capacity as a means of stimulating domestic production.</p>
		
		
