				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In the long term, the rapidly expanding global population and increased purchasing power of consumers in emerging economies are likely to put a strain on many raw materials, including cocoa. Multinational cocoa traders and chocolate companies are putting considerable effort into increasing world production by increasing yields and improving agricultural practices, as competition for land intensifies.&nbsp;</p><p>For example, in Côte d’Ivoire some cocoa producers are going into rubber production, which gives more regular financial revenues throughout the year. In recent years, cocoa prices have been high, but if they decrease there is a risk that more planters will turn to other crops that give them more stable returns. Chocolate companies are looking ahead and trying to secure long-term, high-level, sustainable production in order to be able to respond to an increasing yet changing structure of global demand.</p><p>Within this quest for increased production, there is a growing emphasis from companies, in response to consumer pressures, on promoting sustainable modes of production that avoid exploitation of child labour. There is also a growing focus on enhancing local value-added processing in developing countries.</p>
		</div>
		
